# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-national-university
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000-000] In standard form, it is written as **1 × 109**.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000-000] The metric prefix giga indicates 1,000,000,000 times the base unit.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000-000] One billion years may be called an *eon* in astronomy or geology.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000-000] Previously in British English (but not in American English), the word "billion" referred exclusively to a million millions (1,000,000,000,000).
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000-000] However, this is not common anymore, and the word has been used to mean one thousand million (1,000,000,000) for several decades.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000-000] The term ***milliard*** could also be used to refer to 1,000,000,000; whereas "milliard" is rarely used in English, variations on this name often appear in other languages.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000-000] In the Indian numbering system, it is known as 100 crore or 1 arab.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000-000] It is a common metric used in macroeconomics when describing national economies.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000] In scientific notation, it is written as 1×106 or 106.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000] Physical quantities can also be expressed using the SI prefix mega (M), when dealing with SI units; for example, 1 megawatt (1 MW) equals 1,000,000 watts.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000] The meaning of the word "million" is common to the short scale and long scale numbering systems, unlike the larger numbers, which have different names in the two systems.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000] The million is sometimes used in the English language as a metaphor for a very large number, as in "Not in a million years" and "You're one in a million", or a hyperbole, as in "I've walked a million miles" and "You've asked a million-dollar question".
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000] Even though it is often stressed that counting to precisely a million would be an exceedingly tedious task due to the time and concentration required, there are many ways to bring the number "down to size" in approximate quantities, ignoring irregularities or packing effects.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000] In Indian English and Pakistani English, it is also expressed as 10 lakh.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000] Lakh is derived from *lakṣa* for 100,000 in Sanskrit.
[src:australian-national-university/1-000-000] There are 78,498 primes less than 106, where 999,983 is the largest prime number smaller than 1,000,000.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] The **3rd Battalion** was an infantry battalion of the Australian Army.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Originally raised as part of the First Australian Imperial Force for service during World War I, the battalion formed part of the 1st Brigade, attached to the 1st Division.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] It was formed shortly after the war broke out and was among the first Australian units to be sent overseas, arriving in Egypt in December 1914.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In April 1915 the battalion participated in the Landing at Anzac Cove, coming ashore in the second and third waves.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In December 1915 the 3rd Battalion was evacuated from the Gallipoli peninsula and withdrawn to Egypt again, where it took part in the defence of the Suez Canal before being sent to France to fight on the Western Front in March 1916.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] For the next two and a half years the unit would serve in the trenches in France and Belgium and would take part in many of the major battles fought during that time.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In May 1919, following the end of the war, the battalion was disbanded and its personnel repatriated back to Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1921, the AIF was officially disbanded and the previously existing militia units of the Australian Military Forces were reorganised in order to perpetuate the designations and battle honours of their associated AIF units.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] As a result, the 3rd Battalion (The Werriwa Regiment), was raised around the area to the west of Sydney.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Following the outbreak of World War II, many members of the battalion volunteered for service with the Second Australian Imperial Force and were allocated to the 2/3rd Battalion, with whom they served in North Africa, Syria, Greece, Crete and then later in New Guinea.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1942, following the entry of Japan into the war, the 3rd Battalion (The Werriwa Regiment) was mobilised and brought up to its full wartime establishment with national servicemen.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In May 1942 the battalion was sent to Port Moresby, where it joined the rest of the 30th Brigade, to undertake garrison duties.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In July the Japanese landed around Gona and as reinforcements were brought up from Australia, elements of the 30th Brigade began a number of delaying actions around Kokoda.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In September 1942, the 3rd Battalion was sent up the Kokoda Trail, where it had the distinction of being one of only two militia units to fight alongside its associated AIF unit.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Over the next couple of months it assisted in the recapturing of Kokoda, before participating in the fighting around Buna and Gona.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1943, the battalion was withdrawn to Australia along with the rest of the 30th Brigade, where it was subsequently disbanded in July and its personnel absorbed into its associated AIF unit, the 2/3rd Battalion.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1948, the battalion was re-raised as part of the Citizens Military Force, based around Canberra.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1960, when the Australian Army was reorganised along Pentropic lines, the battalion was reduced to a company-sized unit and formed 'C' Company, 3rd Battalion, Royal New South Wales Regiment (3 RNSWR).
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1965, this company was expanded to become a full battalion again when the Pentropic divisional structure was abandoned; however, in 1987, 3 RNSWR was amalgamated with 4 RNSWR to form the 4th/3rd Battalion, Royal New South Wales Regiment.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Due to the provisions of the *Defence Act 1903* which precluded sending conscripts overseas to fight, following the outbreak of World War I it was decided to raise an all volunteer force, outside of the already existing militia organisation, known as the Australian Imperial Force (AIF).
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Many members of the militia joined up and to a large extent, where possible, the AIF battalions were formed on a territorial basis, which meant that many of the AIF units were able to maintain the identity of their associated militia units.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] The 3rd Battalion, AIF, was raised soon after the declaration of war, and began concentrating at Randwick, drawing its recruits from the Werriwa area of New South Wales.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] The militia unit that was operating in the area at that time was the 43rd (Werriwa) Infantry Regiment, a regiment that could trace its lineage back to 1869.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] After two months, during which time the battalion undertook a period of basic training, the 3rd Battalion departed Australia, proceeding to Egypt, where they arrived on 2 December 1914.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] After undertaking another period of training in Egypt, the battalion was employed in the defence of the Suez Canal, before being committed to the Gallipoli Campaign.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] On 25 April 1915, the 3rd Battalion took part in the landing at Anzac Cove, going ashore with the second and third waves.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] As a stalemate settled over the peninsula the battalion was involved in the defence of the beachhead, before taking part in the Battle of Lone Pine in August.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] It was during this battle, at Sasse's Sap, that Private John Hamilton, performed the deeds that led to him receiving the Victoria Cross.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] For the next four months the battalion remained at Gallipoli, before being evacuated along with the rest of the allied forces, in December 1915.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] After the withdrawal from Gallipoli, the battalion returned to Egypt where they were once again used in the defence of the Suez Canal against the Turks and the AIF undertook a period of reorganisation and expansion.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In March 1916, the 3rd Battalion embarked for France, where for the next two and a half years it would serve in the trenches along the Western Front.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Following a period of acclimatisation where the battalion undertook duties in a quiet sector of the line, in July 1916 the battalion took part in its first major action in Europe, during the Battle of Pozières.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Later they took part in the fighting around Ypres in Belgium, before returning to the Somme to man the line during the winter.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Throughout 1917, they were involved in operations against the Hindenburg Line, spending a majority of the year in the line near Ypres.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1918, the battalion was used to help stop the German spring offensive in March and April, before taking part in the final Allied offensive launched near Amiens on 8 August 1918, which ultimately brought an end to the war.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] As a part of this offensive, the 3rd Battalion continued operations until late September 1918, when they were withdrawn for rest and reorganisation.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] They were out of the line when the Armistice was declared on 11 November 1918 and following that the slow process of demobilisation and repatriation of men began.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] By May 1919, the majority of the battalion's personnel had been returned to Australia for discharge and the battalion was disbanded.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] During the course of its involvement in the war, the 3rd Battalion suffered 3,598 casualties, of which 1,312 were killed in action.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] During the war, while the units of the AIF had been overseas fighting in Europe and the Middle East, the militia units had remained in Australia on home service, providing security at ports, defence installations and other facilities of importance to the war effort.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] However, due to the large numbers of militiamen that volunteered for service with the AIF many of these units were greatly depleted and it was not until after the war, in 1919, that the compulsory training scheme began again.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1921 the AIF was officially disbanded and the following month it was decided to reorganise the militia units and to redesignate them in order to perpetuate the identity of the AIF units that had fought in the war.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] As a result of this decision, and due to the links that the 3rd Battalion, AIF, had with the 43rd (Werriwa) Infantry Regiment, this unit was reformed and designated as the 3rd Battalion (The Werriwa Regiment) and inherited that unit's battle honours.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1929, the compulsory training scheme was suspended following the election of the Scullin Labor government.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] This, coupled with the economic hardships of the Great Depression and the general apathy towards defence matters in this time, meant that the unit's numbers fell rapidly and so, in 1930, the battalion was amalgamated with the 4th Battalion (Australian Rifles).
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] These two units would remain linked until 1937, when they were delinked and the 3rd Battalion amalgamated with the 53rd Battalion (West Sydney Regiment), to form the 3rd/53rd Battalion (Werriwa and West Sydney Regiment).
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] This did not last for very long, though, and shortly after the two units were delinked and the 3rd Battalion was assigned to the 14th Brigade, based around Goulburn with the 55th Battalion (New South Wales Rifle Regiment).
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] When World War II began it was again decided to form an all volunteer force for overseas service.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Nevertheless, large numbers of militiamen volunteered for service in the AIF.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Once again there was an attempt to preserve the territorial identity of the militia units and as a result, many men from the 3rd Battalion (Werriwa Regiment) were allocated to the 2/3rd Battalion, which was raised at Ingleburn in October 1939.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] This unit would later go on to participate in the fighting in North Africa, Greece, Crete, Syria and then later in New Guinea.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Meanwhile, in January 1940, the compulsory training scheme which had been suspended since 1929 was reintroduced and units of the militia were progressively called up for periods of full-time training in order to boost their readiness.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] The 3rd Battalion's base from 1941 to 1942 was in the drill hall built in 1940 in Canberra, now the Drill Hall Gallery, owned by the Australian National University and heritage-listed in 2004.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In January 1942, following the Japanese attacks on Pearl Harbor and the British in Malaya, the situation in the Pacific worsened and many Australians began to worry about invasion.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] As a result of this many of the militia units were mobilised in this time and a number of them were sent to New Guinea to carry out defensive duties.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] The 3rd Battalion was one of these and upon mobilisation it was brought up to its wartime establishment with a number of drafts of national servicemen recruited from regional New South Wales and the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] The battalion began training in earnest near Maitland, New South Wales, before being sent along with the rest of the 14th Brigade to the coast to undertake defensive duties near Newcastle.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In May they were relieved from these duties and returned to camp near Maitland, before going on leave prior to deployment overseas.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] By the end of the month the 3rd Battalion had arrived in Port Moresby where they began garrison duties as part of the 14th Brigade and alongside the 30th Brigade, which consisted of the 39th and 49th Battalions.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In July the New Guinea campaign began when the Japanese landed troops near Buna and began to move inland.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In an effort to delay their advance in time for reinforcements to arrive from Australia, elements of 39th Battalion began a series of delaying actions around Kokoda, while the 3rd Battalion remained in Port Moresby to defend the seaport.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In early September, as reinforcements began to arrive, the battalion moved up the Kokoda Trail to Ioribaiwa, where they began patrolling operations under the command of the 21st Brigade in order to defend the village against advancing Japanese elements.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Alongside the 2/6th Independent Company and the 2/14th and 2/16th Battalions, the 3rd Battalion helped hold the village for four days before falling back to Imita Ridge on 17 September.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Soon after the Japanese, having reached the limit of their supply lines, began to withdraw and the 3rd Battalion subsequently participated in the advance back up the Kokoda Trail, carrying out patrolling operations as they re-occupied numerous villages that had been lost earlier in the campaign.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Late in October, after the Second Battle of Eora Creek – Templeton's Crossing, the battalion was withdrawn from the line for a brief period of rest at Myola, before assuming defensive responsibilities for Kokoda village on 3 November 1942.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] The battalion joined the Australian pursuit towards the Kumusi, taking part in the fighting around Oivi–Gorari before taking part in the fighting around Buna and Gona later in the month.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Around this time, the battalion's machine gun company was detached and in conjunction with several other Militia machine gun companies, it was used to form the 7th Machine Gun Battalion.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In early 1943, the battalion was brought back to Australia for reorganisation.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Based on the Atherton Tablelands in Queensland, the battalion was brought back up to establishment and the 30th Brigade was transferred to the 6th Division, with a view to participating in further operations in New Guinea.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] However, in July it was decided to disband the brigade, to provide reinforcements for the rest of the 6th Division.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] This was only short-lived, though, for later this unit was absorbed by the 2/3rd Battalion.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Members of the battalion received the following decorations: one Distinguished Service Order, two Military Crosses and five Military Medals.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] In 1948, the 3rd Battalion (Werriwa Regiment) was re-raised as part of the Citizens Military Force (CMF), which was the forerunner to the Australian Army Reserve that currently exists.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] This time the battalion was based around Canberra, with depots around regional New South Wales.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] As had been the case following World War I, it was decided that the units of the CMF would become the custodians of the battle honours earned by the AIF during World War II, and thus the battle honours of the 2/3rd Battalion were passed to the Werriwa Regiment.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] Between 1951 and 1960 a national service scheme operated and the battalion's numbers remained reasonably steady, however, in 1960 the scheme was suspended once more and the Australian Army was reorganised with the introduction of the Pentropic divisional structure.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] As a result of this the CMF was greatly reduced and fourteen infantry battalions were disbanded altogether, while many others were amalgamated into the battalions of the six State-based regiments.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] As a result of this, the 3rd Battalion was reduced to a company-sized element of the 3rd Battalion, Royal New South Wales Regiment, forming 'C' Company.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] As a result, 'C' Company, 3 RNSWR was used to re-raise the 3rd Battalion in its own right.
[src:australian-national-university/3rd-battalion-australia] This unit would remain in existence until 1987, when further reforms to the Army Reserve led to a reduction in the number of infantry units across Australia and 3 RNSWR was amalgamated with 4 RNSWR to form the 4th/3rd Battalion, Royal New South Wales Regiment.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Hope was born in Cooma, New South Wales.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] His father was a Presbyterian minister and his mother a teacher.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] He was educated partly at home and in Tasmania, where they moved in 1911.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] He attended Fort Street High School, the University of Sydney whilst residing at St.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Andrew's College and then the University of Oxford on a scholarship.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Returning to Australia in 1931 he then trained as a teacher, and spent some time drifting.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] He worked as a psychologist with the New South Wales Department of Labour and Industry, and as a lecturer in Education and English at Sydney Teachers' College (1937–44).
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] He was a lecturer at the University of Melbourne from 1945 to 1950, and in 1951 became the first professor of English at the newly founded Canberra University College, later of the Australian National University (ANU) when the two institutions merged.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] At the ANU he and Tom Inglis Moore created the first full year course in Australian literature at an Australian university.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] He retired from the ANU in 1968 and was appointed Emeritus Professor.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] He was appointed an Officer of the Order of the British Empire in 1972 and a Companion of the Order of Australia in 1981 and awarded many other honours.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] He died in Canberra, having suffered dementia in his last years, and is buried at the Queanbeyan Lawn Cemetery.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Although he was published as a poet while still young, *The Wandering Islands* (1955) was his first collection and all that remained of his early work after most of his manuscripts were destroyed in a fire.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Its publication was delayed by concern about the effects of Hope's highly erotic and savagely satirical verse on the Australian public.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] His frequent allusions to sexuality in his work caused Douglas Stewart to dub him "Phallic Alec" in a letter to Norman Lindsay.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] His influences were Pope and the Augustan poets, Auden, and Yeats.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] He was a polymath, very largely self-taught, and with a talent for offending his countrymen.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] He wrote a book of "answers" to other poems, including one in response to the poem "To His Coy Mistress" by Andrew Marvell.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] The reviews he wrote in the 1940s and '50s were feared "for their acidity and intelligence.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] If his reviews hurt some writers – Patrick White included – they also sharply raised the standard of literary discussion in Australia." However, Hope relaxed in later years.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] As poet Kevin Hart writes, "The man I knew, from 1973 to 2000, was invariably gracious and benevolent".
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Hope wrote in a letter to the poet and academic Catherine Cole: "Now I feel I've reached the pinnacle of achievement when you equate me with one of Yeats's 'wild, wicked old men'.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] I'm probably remarkably wicked but not very wild, I fear too much ingrained Presbyterian caution".
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Cole suggests that Hope represented the three attributes that Vladimir Nabokov believed essential in a writer, "storyteller, teacher, enchanter".
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Hope's editor and fellow critic was David Brooks who was responsible for posthumously publishing the Selected Poetry and Prose of AD Hope in January, 2000.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Kevin Hart, reviewing Catherine Cole's memoir of Hope, writes that "When A.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Hope died in 2000 at the age of 93, Australia lost its greatest living poet".
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] Hart goes on to say that when once asked what poets could do for Australia, Hope replied "oh not much, merely justify its existence".
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] In 1998 a celebration of his life and works, *The Scythe Honed Fine*, was published by the National Library of Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/a-d-hope] They had a daughter, Emily, who predeceased her parents in 1979, and two sons, Andrew and Geoffrey, who survived him.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:australian-national-university/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] The **Government of the Australian Capital Territory**, also known as the **Australian Capital Territory Government** or **ACT Government**, is the executive branch of the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] The leader of the party or coalition that holds the confidence of the Australian Capital Territory Legislative Assembly forms government.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Unlike the Australian states and the Northern Territory, the Legislative Assembly directly elects one of its number to serve as Chief Minister as the head of the government, rather than being appointed by a Governor or Administrator.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Since December 2014, the Chief Minister has been Andrew Barr, leader of the Labor Party.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Following the 2024 ACT election, Labor formed a minority government of 10 members, after the Greens moved to the crossbench and, dissolving the coalition that had been in place since 2012.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Ministers are appointed by the Chief Minister.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] The current ministry of the Australian Capital Territory (Fourth Barr Ministry) consists of eight of the 25 members of the Legislative Assembly.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] The ACT has internal self-government, but Australia's Constitution does not afford the territory government the full legislative independence provided to Australian states.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Government for the Australian Capital Territory is outlined in Commonwealth legislation; the Australian Capital Territory (Self-Government) Act 1988.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Nonetheless, the ACT is governed according to the principles of the Westminster System, a form of parliamentary government based on the model of the United Kingdom.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Legislative power rests with the unicameral Australian Capital Territory Legislative Assembly.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Executive power rests formally with the executive, which consists of the chief minister and ministers, and is informally called the Cabinet.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Judicial power is exercised by the Supreme Court of the Australian Capital Territory and a system of subordinate courts, but the High Court of Australia and other federal courts have overriding jurisdiction on matters which fall under the ambit of the Australian Constitution.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] The ACT does not have a separate system of local government such as that seen in the Australian States and the Northern Territory.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] In the ACT, government functions that would usually be handled by local government are instead directly handled by the territory government.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] The current arrangement of the incumbent ministry (Fourth Barr Ministry) of the ACT was appointed on 6 November 2024, comprising eight Labor Party members.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] The current arrangement of the incumbent shadow ministry was announced on 4 December 2025, comprising eight Liberal Party members, with a minor reshuffle on 16 April 2026 to add a Men and Men's Health portfolio.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] The ACT Government is served by a unified ACT Public Service agency, reporting to a single Head of Service.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Administrative units, known as directorates, are grouped under areas of portfolio responsibility.
[src:australian-national-university/act-government] Each directorate is led by a director-general who reports to one or more ministers.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The **Australian National University** (**ANU**) is a public research university and member of the Group of Eight, located in Canberra, the capital of Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Its main campus in Acton encompasses seven teaching and research colleges, in addition to several national academies and institutes.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Established in 1946, ANU is the only university to have been created by the Parliament of Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] It traces its origins to Canberra University College, which was established in 1929 and was integrated into ANU in 1960.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU enrolls 10,252 undergraduate and 7,128 postgraduate students and employs 4,517 staff.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The university's endowment stood at A$1.8 billion as of 2018.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU counts six Nobel laureates and 49 Rhodes scholars among its faculty and alumni.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The university has educated the incumbent Governor-General of Australia, two former prime ministers, and more than a dozen current heads of government departments of Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The latest releases of ANU's scholarly publications are held through ANU Press online.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The entry requirements of many programmes are selective with high ATAR scores requirements.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU has consistently been ranked as one of the best universities in Australia, ranking Number 1 in multiple university rankings as of 2023.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Calls for the establishment of a national university in Australia began as early as 1900.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] After the location of the nation's capital, Canberra, was determined in 1908, land was set aside for the ANU at the foot of Black Mountain in the city designs by Walter Burley Griffin.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Establishment of the university was disrupted by World War II but resumed with the creation of the Department of Post-War Reconstruction in 1942, ultimately leading to the passage of the *Australian National University Act 1946* by the Chifley government on 1 August 1946.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The group also included a New Zealander, Sir Raymond Firth (a professor of anthropology at LSE), who had earlier worked in Australia for some years.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Economist Sir Douglas Copland was appointed as ANU's first Vice-Chancellor and former Prime Minister Stanley Bruce served as the first Chancellor.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU was originally organised into four centres—the Research Schools of Physical Sciences, Social Sciences and Pacific Studies and the John Curtin School of Medical Research.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The first residents' hall, University House, was opened in 1954 for faculty members and postgraduate students.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Mount Stromlo Observatory, established by the federal government in 1924, became part of ANU in 1957.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The first locations of the ANU Library, the Menzies and Chifley buildings, opened in 1963.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The Australian Forestry School, located in Canberra since 1927, was amalgamated by ANU in 1965.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Canberra University College (CUC) was the first institution of higher education in the national capital, having been established in 1929 and enrolling its first undergraduate pupils in 1930.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Its founding was led by Sir Robert Garran, one of the drafters of the Australian Constitution and the first Solicitor-General of Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] CUC was affiliated with the University of Melbourne and its degrees were granted by that university.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Academic leaders at CUC included historian Manning Clark, political scientist Finlay Crisp, poet A.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In 1960, CUC was integrated into ANU as the School of General Studies, initially with faculties in arts, economics, law and science.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Faculties in Oriental studies and engineering were introduced later.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Bruce Hall, the first residential college for undergraduates, opened in 1961.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The Canberra School of Music and the **Canberra School of Art** combined in 1988 to form the **Canberra Institute of the Arts**, and amalgamated with the university as the **ANU Institute of the Arts** in 1992.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU established its Medical School in 2002, after obtaining federal government approval in 2000.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] On 18 January 2003, the Canberra bushfires largely destroyed the Mount Stromlo Observatory.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU astronomers now conduct research from the Siding Spring Observatory, which contains 10 telescopes including the Anglo-Australian Telescope.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In February 2013, financial entrepreneur and ANU graduate Graham Tuckwell made the largest university donation in Australian history by giving $50 million to fund an undergraduate scholarship program at ANU.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU is well known for its history of student activism and, in recent years, its fossil fuel divestment campaign, which is one of the longest-running and most successful in the country.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] As of 2014 ANU holds investments in major fossil fuel companies.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] A survey conducted by the Australian Human Rights Commission in 2017 found that the ANU had the second-highest incidence of sexual assault and sexual harassment.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] 3.5 per cent of respondents from the ANU reported being sexually assaulted in 2016.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Vice Chancellor Brian Schmidt apologised to victims of sexual assault and harassment.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The ANU had funding and staff cuts in the School of Music in 2011–15 and in the School of Culture, History and Language in 2016.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] However, there is a range of global (governmental) endowments available for Arts and Social Sciences, designated only for ANU.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU has exchange agreements in place for its students with many foreign universities, most notably in the Asia-Pacific region, including the National University of Singapore, the University of Tokyo, the University of Hong Kong, Peking University, Tsinghua University and Seoul National University.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In 2017, Chinese hackers infiltrated the computers of Australian National University, potentially compromising national security research conducted at the university.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The main campus of ANU extends across the Canberra suburb of Acton, which consists of 358 acres (1.45 km2) of mostly parkland with university buildings landscaped within.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU is roughly bisected by Sullivans Creek, part of the Murray–Darling basin, and is bordered by the native bushland of Black Mountain, Lake Burley Griffin, the suburb of Turner and the Canberra central business district.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The Acton campus is also home to three sports fields (South Oval, Fellows Oval and Willows Oval), six tennis courts (home to the ANU Tennis Club), two gymnasiums and a pool.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Many university sites are of historical significance dating from the establishment of the national capital, with over 40 buildings recognised by the Commonwealth Heritage List and several others on local lists.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] With over 10,000 trees on its campus, ANU won an International Sustainable Campus Network Award in 2009 and was ranked the 2nd greenest university campus in Australia in 2011.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Four of Australia's five learned societies are based at ANU—the Australian Academy of Science, the Australian Academy of the Humanities, the Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia and the Australian Academy of Law.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The Australian National Centre for the Public Awareness of Science and the National Film and Sound Archive are also located at ANU, while the National Museum of Australia and CSIRO are situated next to the campus.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU occupies additional locations including Mount Stromlo Observatory on the outskirts of Canberra, Siding Spring Observatory near Coonabarabran, a campus at Kioloa on the South Coast of New South Wales and a research unit in Darwin.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The Drill Hall Gallery is housed a drill hall dating from the 1940s, for use in training soldiers for the Second World War, and as base for 3rd Battalion, Werriwa Regiment.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The interior was remodelled to create an art gallery in 1984, and in 2004 the building was heritage-listed.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Temporary exhibitions of the national collection were held in the hall while the National Gallery of Australia was being built.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU took over the hall in 1992 to exhibit its own collection of artworks, and also as a venue for temporary exhibitions.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] There are four separate exhibition spaces, which provide the venues not only for exhibitions developed by or in collaboration with the university, but also to accompany major conferences and public events.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The venue hosts both national and international exhibitions.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Sidney Nolan's panorama, *Riverbend*, which comprises nine panels, ís on permanent display at the Drill Hall Gallery.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU is governed by a 15-member Council, whose members include the Chancellor and Vice-Chancellor.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Gareth Evans, a former Foreign Minister of Australia, was ANU Chancellor from 2010 to December 2019 and Brian Schmidt, an astrophysicist and Nobel Laureate, served as Vice-Chancellor from 1 January 2016 to 1 January 2024.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Evans was succeeded as Chancellor by a fellow former Foreign Minister, Julie Bishop, in January 2020.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Schmidt was succeeded as Vice-Chancellor by cultural anthropologist and Distinguished Professor Genevieve Bell in January 2024.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU was reorganised in 2006 to create seven Colleges, each of which leads both teaching and research.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Additional restructuring occurred in 2017, resulting in changes to the names and schools within the Colleges.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The ANU College of Arts and Social Sciences is divided into the Research School of Social Sciences (RSSS) and Research School of Humanities and the Arts (RSHA).
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] RSHA contains schools of Archaeology and Anthropology; Art & Design; and Literature, Languages and Linguistics, the latter of which include departments focusing on Linguistics & Applied Linguistics; English, Screen, Drama & Gender Studies; Languages & Cultures, and Classical Studies.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] RSHA also houses the ANU School of Music.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In 2017, ANU ranked 6th in the world for politics, 8th in the world for Social Policy and Administration and 11th in the world for development studies.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The college is also home to the Australian Studies Institute.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The ANU College of Asia and the Pacific is a specialist centre of Asian and Pacific studies and languages, among the largest collections of experts in these fields of any university in the English-speaking world.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The college also houses the Australian Centre on China in the World, the Strategic and Defence Studies Centre, and the Council for Security Cooperation in the Asia Pacific, Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] It has dedicated regional institutes for China, Indonesia, Japan, Korea, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, the Pacific, Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The college hosts a series annual and biannual updates, on various regions in the Asia-Pacific.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The Crawford School of Public Policy also hosts offices and programs for the Australia and New Zealand School of Government.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Many high performing Year in Asia program students gain the opportunity to travel to an Asian country of their choosing to study for one year specializing in one Asian language.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The college also has affiliation with Indiana University's Pan Asia Institute.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] It also has membership of the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The ANU College of Systems and Society brings together critical capabilities in understanding the modern interfaces between systems, technology, processes, the physical world, and the social world.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The college comprises six academic units: the Australian National Centre for the Public Awareness of Science, Fenner School of Environment & Society, Mathematical Sciences Institute, School of Computing, School of Cybernetics, and School of Engineering.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU is home to the National Computational Infrastructure National Facility and was a co-founder of NICTA, the chief information and communications technology research centre in Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The ANU College of Law, Governance and Policy comprises the ANU Law School and ANU School of Legal Practice.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The college covers legal research and teaching, with centres dedicated to commercial law, international law, public law and environmental law.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In addition to numerous research programs, the college offers the professional LL.B. and J.D. degrees.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] It is the 7th oldest of Australia's 36 law schools and was ranked 2nd among Australian and 12th among world law schools by the 2018 QS Rankings.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Students are given the chance to spend three weeks in Geneva concerning the institutional practice of International Law.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The ANU College of Science and Medicine comprises the Research Schools of Astronomy & Astrophysics, Biology, Chemistry, Earth Sciences, and Physics.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Under the direction of Mark Oliphant, nuclear physics was one of the university's most notable early research priorities, leading to the construction of a 500 megajoule homopolar generator and a 7.7 megaelectronvolts cyclotron in the 1950s.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] These devices were to be used as part of a 10.6 gigaelectronvolt synchrotron particle accelerator that was never completed, however they remained in use for other research purposes.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU has been home to eight particle accelerators over the years and operates the 14UD and LINAS accelerators.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Brian Schmidt (astrophysicist at Mount Stromlo Observatory) received the 2011 Nobel Prize for Physics for his work on the accelerating expansion of the universe.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The ANU College of Science & Medicine encompasses the John Curtin School of Medical Research (JCSMR), ANU Medical School, National Centre for Epidemiology and Population Health, and Research School of Psychology.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] JCSMR was established in 1948 as a result of the vision of Nobel laureate Howard Florey.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Three further Nobel Prizes have been won as a result of research at JCSMR—in 1963 by John Eccles and in 1996 by Peter Doherty and Rolf M.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] At the end of 2018, ANU recorded an endowment of A$1.8 billion.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU is a member of the Group of Eight, Association of Pacific Rim Universities, the International Alliance of Research Universities, UNESCO Chairs, U7 Alliance, Winter Institute. and Global Scholars Program.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU participates in the US Financial Direct Loan program.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The RG Menzies Scholarship to Harvard University is awarded annually to at least one talented Australian who has gained admission to a Harvard graduate school.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU and University of Melbourne are the only two Australian partner universities of Yale University's Fox Fellowship program.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU has exchange partnership with Yale University, Brown University, MIT and Oxford University, and ANU has a research partnership with Harvard University.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The library of ANU originated in 1948 with the appointment of the first librarian, Arthur McDonald.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The library holds over 2.5 million physical volumes distributed across six branches—the Chifley, Menzies, Hancock, Art & Music, and Law Libraries and the external Print Repository.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Chifley and Hancock libraries are both accessible for ANU staff and students 24 hours a day.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] For international students starting in 2025, tuition fees range from A$32,020 to A$95,360 per academic year for award programs lasting at least one year.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Domestic students may be offered a federally-subsidised Commonwealth Supported Place (CSP) which substantially decreases the student contribution amount billed to the student.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The maximum student contribution amount limits that can be applied to CSP students are dependent on the field of study.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Since 2021, Commonwealth Supported Places have also been limited to 7 years of equivalent full-time study load (EFTSL), calculated in the form of Student Learning Entitlement (SLE).
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Students may accrue additional SLE under some circumstances (e.g. starting a *separate* one-year honours program) or every 10 years.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Domestic students are also able to access the HECS-HELP student loans scheme offered by the federal government.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] These are indexed to the Consumer or Wage Price Index, whichever is lower, and repayments are voluntary unless the recipient passes an income threshold.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The university also offers several scholarships, which come in the form of bursaries or tuition fee remission.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In the 2024 *Aggregate Ranking of Top Universities*, which measures aggregate performance across the QS, THE and ARWU rankings, the university attained a position of #57 (6th nationally).
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In the *Australian Financial Review* Best Universities Ranking 2025, the university was ranked #5 amongst Australian universities.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In the 2026 *Quacquarelli Symonds* World University Rankings (published 2025), the university attained a tied position of #32 (4th nationally).
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In the *Times Higher Education* World University Rankings 2026 (published 2025), the university attained a tied position of #73 (4th nationally).
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In the 2025 *Academic Ranking of World Universities*, the university attained a position of #101–150 (tied 6–7th nationally).
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] News & World Report* Best Global Universities, the university attained a position of #86 (7th nationally).
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In the *CWTS Leiden Ranking* 2024, the university attained a position of #238 (10th nationally).
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The Australian Government's QILT conducts national surveys documenting the student life cycle from enrolment through to employment.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] These surveys place more emphasis on criteria such as student experience, graduate outcomes and employer satisfaction than perceived reputation, research output and citation counts.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In the 2023 Employer Satisfaction Survey, graduates of the university had an overall employer satisfaction rate of 84.2%.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In the 2023 Graduate Outcomes Survey, graduates of the university had a full-time employment rate of 80.7% for undergraduates and 88.5% for postgraduates.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The initial full-time salary was A$72,000 for undergraduates and A$96,400 for postgraduates.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In the 2023 Student Experience Survey, undergraduates at the university rated the quality of their entire educational experience at 79.4% meanwhile postgraduates rated their overall education experience at 72.5%.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Australian National University Students' Association (ANUSA) is the students' union of the Australian National University and acts as a representative body for the undergraduate, postgraduate and research students.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The Australian National University Union is another student association that manages catering, retail outlets and other amenities on behalf of all students.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The magazine was originally published by the school's student association.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] An independent student organization called ANU Student Media was incorporated in October 2010, and has operated *Woroni* ever since.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In 2012, an online radio station called Woroni Radio was launched, and a video production arm called Woroni TV was started in 2017.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] This newspaper has been digitised as part of the Australian Newspapers Digitisation Program of the National Library of Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] As of January 2015, issues dating from 1950 to 2007 are available via Trove.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Digital versions of works published since 2011 are uploaded and available in colour on electronic publishing platform issuu.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Eleven on-campus residential halls are affiliated with ANU—Bruce Hall, Burgmann College, Burton & Garran Hall, Fenner Hall, John XXIII College, Ursula Hall, Wamburun Hall, Wright Hall, Yukeembruk Village, Graduate House and Toad Hall.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Together these residence accommodate for undergraduate and postgraduate students.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Four UniLodge residences are also available to ANU students, situated just off campus—Davey Lodge, Kinloch Lodge, Warrumbul Lodge and Lena Karmel Lodge.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In 2010, the non-residential Griffin Hall was established for students living off-campus.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Another off-campus student accommodation was launched by UniGardens Pty, University Gardens located in Belconnen.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Bruce Hall opened in 1961, and was the first undergraduate hall of residence at the university and the first mixed-gender undergraduate residence in Australia.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In 2014, 2019 and 2020 there were major protests organised by student leaders across all of the ANU's halls of residence against steep rent hikes, neglect of pastoral care support, and repeated failures to address issues relating to sexual assault and sexual harassment.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Though supported by a majority of students living on residence, the ANU's response to past protests has been mixed, with many recommendations and requests for student consultations ignored.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The outcome of the 2020 protests revolve around demands for stronger SASH policy, accountability surrounding tariff rises, and commitments to adequate pastoral care; the outcome of these protests is as yet unknown.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Protests have been held since on the issue, with one high-profile one occurring on the same day as the annual Open Day in 2024.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Notable past faculty include Mark Oliphant, Keith Hancock, Manning Clark, Derek Freeman, H.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Coombs, Gareth Evans, John Crawford, Hedley Bull, Frank Fenner, C.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Basham, Bernhard Neumann, and former Indonesian Vice-president Boediono.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Nobel Prizes have been awarded to former ANU Chancellor Howard Florey and faculty members John Eccles, John Harsanyi, Rolf M.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Zinkernagel, Peter Doherty and Brian Schmidt.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Notable present scholars include Hilary Charlesworth, Ian McAllister, Hugh White, Warwick McKibbin, Keith Dowding, Amin Saikal and Jeremy Shearmur.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Narayanan, Nelson Mandela, Desmond Tutu, Saburo Okita and notable foreign scientists John Cockcroft, Jan Hendrik Oort and Alexander R.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The network of the university was subject to serious compromise from 9 November to 21 December 2018.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ABC News reported that the initial breach occurred when a phishing message was previewed.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] After investigating, the university published a report on the incident.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Cyber safety recommendations are generally applicable.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In September 2023, Alex Ophel (an ex-student) stabbed two female students and assaulted a male student with a frying pan.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] There were several injuries but no fatalities.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] ANU Chancellor Julie Bishop later called for the ACT government to explain why the university was not informed of the risk beforehand.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] In May 2025, the university released the findings of an independent review led by former Victorian Police Commissioner Christine Nixon into gender and cultural issues within the College of Health and Medicine.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] The review, based on interviews with 83 individuals and 67 written submissions, described a "remarkable tolerance" for misconduct, with reporting pathways often compromised by conflicts of interest.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] It identified entrenched dysfunction, a toxic "work until you drop" culture, and significant gender imbalances in senior academic positions.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Since the commissioning of the review in 2024, the university closed the standalone College of Health and Medicine and merged it with the College of Science.
[src:australian-national-university/anu-college-of-arts-and-social-sciences] Vice-Chancellor Genevieve Bell publicly apologised and committed to implementing all 17 recommendations, including structural reform and external monitoring.
